article.description:
Matee Ajavon had 21 points, five assists
and five rebounds in leading Rutgers to its eighth straight win,
69-47 over Seton Hall on Saturday.
article.headline: Ajavon's 21 points carry Rutgers past Seton Hall
article.linkText: No. 5 Rutgers rides Ajavon to eighth straight win
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Seton Hall wanted to show how far it had come. Rutgers let the Pirates know they still have a ways to go.

Matee Ajavon had 21 points, five assists and five rebounds to lead No. 5 Rutgers to its eighth straight win, a 69-47 victory over Seton Hall on Saturday.

Epiphanny Prince had 19 points and 10 rebounds and Kia Vaughn added 10 points and 12 rebounds for the Scarlet Knights (13-2, 3-0 Big East), who beat the Pirates (11-3, 2-1) for the seventh straight time.

Heather Zurich added 12 points on 6-for-7 shooting for the Knights, who are down to eight healthy players after forward Brittany Ray had right knee surgery Saturday morning. She is expected to miss six weeks.

"Ever since I was a freshman, we've always had something to deal with," Ajavon said of the short bench. "Everyone is strong, everyone will work hard and we'll be fine."

Seton Hall got 17 points from Jadis Rhodin and 10 from Amber Harris. But the Pirates, who were brimming with confidence thanks to a seven-game winning streak, had a frigid-shooting start that let Rutgers take a 23-4 lead.

"Hopefully, this is something we can learn from and get better as the year goes on," Seton Hall coach Phyllis Mangina said. "You can't come in and play a team this good and not try to score. If we bang down about three or four of those [early] jumpers, maybe we get settled.

"I'd like to take back the first 11 minutes. That was very uncharacteristic of our team."

Rutgers hit four of its first five shots to open a 9-0 lead and Seton Hall never got closer than eight. The Scarlet Knights aggressive man-to-man defense, which entered the game second in the nation in points allowed, harassed Seton Hall into missing 20 of its first 23 shots.

Rutgers went into the break up 31-14 against the Pirates, who shot 22.6 percent from the field in the first half and 36.8 percent overall.

"We tried to come out strong on the defensive end," Zurich said. "We just wanted to focus on the little things. I didn't even know what the score was at the time, but we were just trying to bring a lot of energy at the beginning."

Ajavon agreed.

"We just had a good rhythm," she said. "I didn't pay attention to the score either, but I knew it felt good."

Seton Hall hit nine of its first 12 shots after intermission to pull within 47-36. Rutgers responded with a 6-0 run and never led by less than 17 points from there.

The best Pirate team in several years hoped a good showing against Rutgers would prove that New Jersey has another strong Big East squad.

"I don't think that's anything personal," Ajavon said. "We play Seton Hall as hard as we'll play any other team. We still want to get things accomplished and obviously win. I don't think it's a state rivalry or anything to that effect."

In shooting 50.9 percent, the Knights moved to 27-7 overall against Seton Hall and have won eight straight home games against the Pirates, who have not won at Rutgers since Jan. 20, 1996. The Knights have won 21 straight against non-ranked opponents.
